{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4642bb9b-eeda-49c6-8df2-43f415fb021c","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9. Here's the modern approach:\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via **constructor** (no more `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property).\n- **Sync init** — use the constructor.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` with `async Task`.\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client = null!;\n\n    // Constructor: sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Async init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public void Cleanup() => _client?.Dispose();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor injection of `TestContext` replaced the legacy settable property in MSTest v3.\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task`, so no need for `.Result` or `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` hacks.\n- Use `[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]` (static) if you need one-time setup shared across all tests in the class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d51af87-631b-4e0a-953e-7c511a5570fc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended way to handle initialization is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest v3+, you can inject `TestContext` via a constructor parameter or via a property. The modern way is constructor injection.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method or constructor.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method (MSTest v3 supports async `[TestInitialize]`).\n\nLet me provide the recommended modern MSTest patterns.\n\n\n---\n\nSo with MSTest 3.x, I can inject `TestContext` directly through the constructor, which is the preferred approach now, and I can use async `[TestInitialize]` methods for any asynchronous setup work. I can mix both approaches—constructor for synchronous initialization and the attribute method for async operations.","outputTokens":625,"requestId":"082F:DA68B:C75E72:E90826:69EAC73F"},"id":"7edd04d3-3095-4b2d-bb48-000ccf091833","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:28:44.018Z","parentId":"85ff5a89-a59d-427a-a87f-ca126ccce239"}
